# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abseil-cpp-lib
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] Because earlier C++ standard revisions were noticeably late, the name "C++1y" was sometimes used instead until its approval, similarly to how the C++11 standard used to be termed "C++0x" with the expectation of its release before 2010 (although in fact it slipped into 2010 and finally 2011).
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] These are the features added to the core language of C++14.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] C++11 allowed lambda functions to deduce the return type based on the type of the expression given to the return statement.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] C++14 provides this ability to all functions.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] It also extends these facilities to lambda functions, allowing return type deduction for functions that are not of the form `return expression;`.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] If multiple return expressions are used in the function's implementation, then they must all deduce the same type.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] Functions that deduce their return types can be forward declared, but they cannot be used until they have been defined.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] Their definitions must be available to the translation unit that uses them.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] In C++11, two methods of type deduction were added.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] `auto` was a way to create a variable of the appropriate type, based on a given expression.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] `decltype` was a way to compute the type of a given expression.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] However, `decltype` and `auto` deduce types in different ways.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] In particular, `auto` always deduces a non-reference type, as though by using `std::decay`, while `auto&&` always deduces a reference type.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] This allows `auto` declarations to use the `decltype` rules on the given expression.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] The `decltype(auto)` syntax can also be used with return type deduction, by using `decltype(auto)` syntax instead of `auto` for the function's return type deduction.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] C++11 introduced the concept of a constexpr-declared function; a function which could be executed at compile time.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] Their return values could be consumed by operations that require constant expressions, such as an integer template argument.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] However, C++11 constexpr functions could only contain a single expression that is returned (as well as `static_assert`s and a small number of other declarations).
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] `goto` statements are forbidden in C++14 relaxed constexpr-declared functions.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] Also, C++11 stated that all non-static member functions that were declared `constexpr` were also implicitly declared `const`, with respect to `this`.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] That has since been removed; non-static member functions may be non-`const`.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] However, per the restrictions above, a non-`const` `constexpr` member function can only modify a class member if that object's lifetime began within the constant expression evaluation.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] In prior versions of C++, only functions, classes or type aliases could be templated.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] C++14 allows the creation of variables that are templated.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] An example given in the proposal is a variable `pi` that can be read to get the value of pi for various types (e.g., `3` when read as an integral type; the closest value possible with `float`, `double` or `long double` precision when read as `float`, `double` or `long double`, respectively; etc.).
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] The usual rules of templates apply to such declarations and definitions, including specialization.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] C++11 added default member initializers, expressions to be applied to members at class scope if a constructor did not initialize the member itself.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] The definition of aggregates was changed to explicitly exclude any class with member initializers; therefore, they are not allowed to use aggregate initialization.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] C++14 relaxes this restriction, allowing aggregate initialization on such types.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] If the braced init list does not provide a value for that argument, the member initializer takes care of it.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] Numeric literals in C++14 can be specified in binary form.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] The syntax uses the prefixes `0b` or `0B`.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] The syntax is also used in other languages e.g.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] Java, C#, Swift, Go, Scala, Ruby, Python, OCaml, and as an unofficial extension in some C compilers since at least 2007.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] In C++14, the single-quote character may be used arbitrarily as a digit separator in numeric literals, both integer literals and floating point literals.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] This can make it easier for human readers to parse large numbers through subitizing.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] In C++11, lambda function parameters need to be declared with concrete types.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] C++14 relaxes this requirement, allowing lambda function parameters to be declared with the `auto` type specifier.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] Concerning `auto` type deduction, generic lambdas follow the rules of template argument deduction (which are similar, but not identical in all respects).
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] Generic lambdas are essentially templated functor lambdas.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] C++11 lambda functions capture variables declared in their outer scope by value-copy or by reference.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] This means that value members of a lambda cannot be move-only types.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] C++14 allows captured members to be initialized with arbitrary expressions.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] This allows both capture by value-move and declaring arbitrary members of the lambda, without having a correspondingly named variable in an outer scope.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] The lambda function `lambda` returns 1, which is what `value` was initialized with.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] The declared capture deduces the type from the initializer expression as if by `auto`.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] The `[[deprecated]]` attribute allows marking an entity deprecated, which makes it still legal to use but puts users on notice that use is discouraged and may cause a warning message to be printed during compilation.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] An optional string literal can appear as the argument of `[[deprecated("Reason")]]`, to explain the rationale for deprecation and suggest a replacement.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] C++14 adds a shared timed mutex and a companion shared lock type.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] The C++ Standard Library defines four associative container classes.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] These classes allow the user to look up a value based on a value of that type.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] The map containers allow the user to specify a key and a value, where lookup is done by key and returns a value.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] However, the lookup is always done by the specific key type, whether it is the key as in maps or the value itself as in sets.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] C++14 allows the lookup to be done via an arbitrary type, so long as the comparison operator can compare that type with the actual key type.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] This would allow a map from `std::string` to some value to compare against a `const char*` or any other type for which an `operator<` overload is available.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] It is also useful for indexing composite objects in a `std::set` by the value of a single member without forcing the user of `find` to create a dummy object (for example creating an entire `struct Person` to find a person by name).
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] To preserve backwards compatibility, heterogeneous lookup is only allowed when the comparator given to the associative container allows it.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] The standard library classes `std::less<>` and `std::greater<>` are augmented to allow heterogeneous lookup.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] C++11 defined the syntax for user-defined literal suffixes, but the standard library did not use any of them.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] The two "s" literals do not clash, as the string one only operates on string literals, and the one for seconds operates only on numbers.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] The `std::tuple` type introduced in C++11 allows an aggregate of typed values to be indexed by a compile-time constant integer.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] C++14 extends this to allow fetching from a tuple by type instead of by index.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] `std::make_unique` can be used like `std::make_shared` for `std::unique_ptr` objects.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] `std::integral_constant` gained an `operator()` overload to return the constant value.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] The class template `std::integer_sequence` and related alias templates were added for representing compile-time integer sequences, such as the indices of elements in a parameter pack.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] The global `std::begin`/`std::end` functions were augmented with `std::cbegin`/`std::cend` functions, which return constant iterators, and `std::rbegin`/`std::rend` and `std::crbegin`/`std::crend` which return reverse iterators.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] The `std::exchange` function template assigns a new value to a variable and returns the old value.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] New overloads of `std::equal`, `std::mismatch`, and `std::is_permutation` take a pair of iterators for the second range, so that the caller does not need to separately check that the two ranges are of the same length.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] The `std::is_final` type trait detects if a class is marked `final`.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] The `std::quoted` stream I/O manipulator allows inserting and extracting strings with embedded spaces, by placing delimiters (defaulting to double-quotes) on output and stripping them on input, and escaping any embedded delimiters.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] Clang finished support for C++14 in 3.4 though under the standard name c++1y, and made C++14 the default C++ standard in Clang 6.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] GCC finished support for C++14 in GCC 5, and made C++14 the default C++ standard in GCC 6.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-14] Microsoft Visual Studio 2017 has implemented "almost all" C++14 features.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] In the C++ programming language, the **C++ Standard Library** is a collection of classes and functions, which are written in the core language and part of the C++ ISO Standard itself.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] The C++ Standard Library also incorporates most headers of the ISO C standard library ending with ".h", but their use was deprecated (reverted the deprecation since C++23).
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] C++23 instead considers these headers as useful for interoperability with C, and recommends against their usage outside of programs that are intended to be both valid C and C++ programs.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] No other headers in the C++ Standard Library end in ".h".
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] Features of the C++ Standard Library are declared within the `std` namespace.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] The C++ Standard Library is based upon conventions introduced by the Standard Template Library (STL), and has been influenced by research in generic programming and developers of the STL such as Alexander Stepanov and Meng Lee.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] Although the C++ Standard Library and the STL share many features, neither is a strict superset of the other.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] The design of the C++ standard library, much like the C standard library, is minimalistic, and contains only core features for programming, lacking most of the more specialised features offered by the Java standard library or C# standard library.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] For more features, some third-party libraries such as Boost libraries and POCO C++ Libraries, which offer additional features, may be used to supplement the standard library.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] An implementation for a C++ standard library header is described as "freestanding" if the execution of the program does not rely on an operating system.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] A noteworthy feature of the C++ Standard Library is that it not only specifies the syntax and semantics of generic algorithms, but also places requirements on their performance.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] These performance requirements often correspond to a well-known algorithm, which is expected but not required to be used.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] In most cases this requires linear time O(*n*) or linearithmic time O(*n* log *n*), but in some cases higher bounds are allowed, such as quasilinear time O(*n* log2 *n*) for stable sort (to allow in-place merge sort).
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] In other cases requirements remain laxer, such as selection, which is only required to be linear on average (as in quickselect), not requiring worst-case linear as in introselect.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] The C++ Standard Library underwent ISO standardization as part of the C++ ISO Standardization effort in the 1990s.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] Since 2011, it has been expanded and updated every three years with each revision of the C++ standard.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] C++20 specifies the introduction of standard library header units, and C++23 adds full module support for the standard library.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] The Apache C++ Standard Library is another open-source implementation.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] It was originally developed commercially by Rogue Wave Software and later donated to the Apache Software Foundation.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] However, after more than five years without a release, the board of the Apache Software Foundation decided to end this project and move it to Apache Attic.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] C++ was designed with systems programming and embedded, resource-constrained software and large systems in mind, with performance, efficiency, and flexibility of use as its design highlights.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), with the latest standard version ratified and published by ISO in October 2024 as *ISO/IEC 14882:2024* (informally known as C++23).
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] The C++ programming language was initially standardized in 1998 as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which was then amended by the C++03, C++11, C++14, C++17, and C++20 standards.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] The next C++23 standard superseded these with new features and an enlarged standard library.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Before the initial standardization in 1998, C++ was developed by Stroustrup at Bell Labs since 1979 as an extension of the C language; he wanted an efficient and flexible language similar to C that also provided high-level features for program organization.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Since 2012, C++ has been on a three-year release schedule with C++29 as the next planned standard.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] In 1979, Bjarne Stroustrup, a Danish computer scientist, began work on "C with Classes", the predecessor to C++.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] The motivation for creating a new language originated from Stroustrup's experience in programming for his PhD thesis.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup found that Simula had features that were very helpful for large software development, but the language was too slow for practical use, while BCPL was fast but too low-level to be suitable for large software development.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] When Stroustrup started working in AT&T Bell Labs, he had the problem of analyzing the UNIX kernel with respect to distributed computing.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Remembering his PhD experience, Stroustrup set out to enhance the C language with Simula-like features.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] C was chosen because it was general-purpose, fast, portable, and widely used.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] In addition to C and Simula's influences, other languages influenced this new language, including ALGOL 68, Ada, CLU, and ML.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Initially, Stroustrup's "C with Classes" added features to the C compiler, Cpre, including classes, derived classes, strong typing, inlining, and default arguments.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] In 1982, Stroustrup began designing a cleaned-up and extended successor to C with Classes, using traditional compiler technology.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] The language was briefly called C84 before the name C++ was adopted; the name was suggested by Rick Mascitti and refers to C's `++` increment operator.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] The resulting language included virtual functions, function and operator overloading, references, `const`, improved type checking, user-controlled free-store memory allocation (`new`/`delete`), and BCPL-style single-line `//` comments.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup also designed and implemented Cfront, the C++ compiler front end, between spring 1982 and summer 1983.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] In 1984, Stroustrup implemented the first stream input/output library.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] The idea of providing an output operator rather than a named output function was suggested by Doug McIlroy (who had previously suggested Unix pipes).
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] In 1985, the first edition of *The C++ Programming Language* was released, which became the definitive reference for the language, as there was not yet an official standard.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] The first commercial implementation of C++ was released in October of the same year.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] In 1989, C++ 2.0 was released, followed by the updated second edition of *The C++ Programming Language* in 1991.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] New features in 2.0 included multiple inheritance, abstract classes, static member functions, const member functions, and protected members.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] In 1990, *The Annotated C++ Reference Manual* was published.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] This work became the basis for the future standard.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Later feature additions included templates, exceptions, namespaces, new casts, and a Boolean type.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, C++98 was released, standardizing the language, and a minor update (C++03) was released in 2003.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] After C++98, C++ evolved relatively slowly until, in 2011, the C++11 standard was released, adding numerous new features, enlarging the standard library further, and providing more facilities to C++ programmers.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] After a minor C++14 update released in December 2014, various new additions were introduced in C++17.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] After becoming finalized in February 2020, a draft of the C++20 standard was approved on 4 September 2020, and officially published on 15 December 2020.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] On January 3, 2018, Stroustrup was announced as the 2018 winner of the Charles Stark Draper Prize for Engineering, "for conceptualizing and developing the C++ programming language".
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] In December 2022, C++ ranked third on the TIOBE index, surpassing Java for the first time in the history of the index.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] As of November 2024, the language ranks second after Python, with Java being in third.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] In March 2025, Stroustrup issued a call for the language community to defend it.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Since the language allows manual memory management, bugs that represent security risks such as buffer overflow may be introduced in programs when inadvertently misused by the programmer.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] According to Stroustrup, "the name signifies the evolutionary nature of the changes from C." This name is credited to Rick Mascitti (mid-1983) and was first used in December 1983.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] When Mascitti was questioned informally in 1992 about the naming, he indicated that it was given in a tongue-in-cheek spirit.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] The name comes from C's `++` operator (which increments the value of a variable) and a common naming convention of using "+" to indicate an enhanced computer program.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] During C++'s development period, the language had been referred to as "new C" and "C with Classes" before acquiring its final name.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by an ISO working group known as JTC1/SC22/WG21.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] The working group holds three week-long meetings each year.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] So far, it has published seven revisions of the C++ standard and is currently working on the next revision, C++26.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, the ISO working group standardized C++ for the first time as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which is informally known as *C++98*.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] In 2003, it published a new version of the C++ standard called *ISO/IEC 14882:2003*, which fixed problems identified in C++98.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] The next major revision of the standard was informally referred to as "C++0x", but it was not released until 2011.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] C++11 (14882:2011) included many additions to both the core language and the standard library.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] In 2014, C++14 (also known as C++1y) was released as a small extension to C++11, featuring mainly bug fixes and small improvements.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] The Draft International Standard ballot procedures completed in mid-August 2014.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] After C++14, a major revision C++17, informally known as C++1z, was completed by the ISO C++ committee in mid July 2017 and was approved and published in December 2017.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] More technical specifications are in development and pending approval.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] The C++ language has two main components: a direct mapping of hardware features provided primarily by the C subset, and zero-overhead abstractions based on those mappings.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup describes C++ as "a light-weight abstraction programming language [designed] for building and using efficient and elegant abstractions"; and "offering both hardware access and abstraction is the basis of C++.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] A hello world program that conforms to the C standard is also a valid C++ hello world program.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] The C++ standard specifies both the core language and the standard library.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] The library clauses describe the contents of the library, how a well-formed C++ program uses it, and the requirements placed on conforming implementations.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] The standard library is organized into areas such as language support, diagnostics, memory management, metaprogramming, general utilities, containers, iterators, ranges, algorithms, strings, text processing, numerics, time, input/output, and concurrency support.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] It also provides the facilities of the C standard library through C++ headers such as `<cstdio>` and `<cstdlib>`; except for names defined as macros in C, these declarations are placed in namespace `std`.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Library facilities are traditionally made available by including standard headers, for example `#include <vector>`.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Since C++20, importable standard library headers may also be imported as header units.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] C++23 added the named standard library modules `std` and `std.compat`: `std` exports declarations in namespace `std`, while `std.compat` also exports corresponding global namespace declarations for C library facilities.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] A major influence on the standard library was the Standard Template Library (STL), a generic programming library proposed to the C++ standards committee by Alexander Stepanov and Meng Lee in 1994.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Its model of containers, iterators, and generic algorithms became part of the Standard C++ Library, although the standard library also includes many other facilities, such as input/output, localization, diagnostics, and the C library subset.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] The main aim is to efficiently and consistently write type and resource safe C++.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Despite this, the guidelines are not endorsed by the ISO C++ standards committee and do not represent the consensus of the committee.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] The Core Guidelines were announced in the opening keynote at CPPCon 2015.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] The Guidelines are accompanied by the Guideline Support Library (GSL), a header-only library of types and functions to implement the Core Guidelines and static checker tools for enforcing Guideline rules.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] One of the largest implementations of this is Microsoft's implementation.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Many of the existing features in the GSL have been later integrated into the language, such as `std::byte`, smart pointers, and `std::span`.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] To give compiler vendors greater freedom, the C++ standards committee decided not to dictate the implementation of name mangling, exception handling, and other implementation-specific features.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] The downside of this decision is that object code produced by different compilers is expected to be incompatible.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] There are, however, attempts to standardize compilers for particular machines or operating systems.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] For example, the Itanium C++ ABI is processor-independent (despite its name) and is implemented by GCC and Clang.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] C++ is often considered to be a superset of C but this is not strictly true.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Most C code can easily be made to compile correctly in C++ but there are a few differences that cause some valid C code to be invalid or behave differently in C++.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] For example, C allows implicit conversion from `void*` to other pointer types but C++ does not (for type safety reasons).
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Also, C++ defines many new keywords, such as `new` and `class`, which may be used as identifiers (for example, variable names) in a C program.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Some incompatibilities have been removed by the 1999 revision of the C standard (C99), which now supports C++ features such as line comments (`//`) and declarations mixed with code.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Some of the C99-introduced features were included in the subsequent version of the C++ standard, C++11 (out of those which were not redundant).
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] However, the C++11 standard introduces new incompatibilities, such as disallowing assignment of a string literal to a character pointer, which remains valid C.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] To intermix C and C++ code, any function declaration or definition that is to be called from/used both in C and C++ must be declared with C linkage by placing it within an `extern "C" {/*...*/}` block.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Such a function may not rely on features depending on name mangling (i.e., function overloading).
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Programs developed in C or C++ often utilize inline assembly to take advantage of its low-level functionalities, greater speed, and enhanced control compared to high-level programming languages when optimizing for performance is essential.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides support for embedding assembly language using asm declarations, but the compatibility of inline assembly varies significantly between compilers and architectures.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Unlike high-level language features such as Python or Java, assembly code is highly dependent on the underlying processor and compiler implementation.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] Different C++ compilers implement inline assembly in distinct ways.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides two primary methods of integrating ASM code: standalone assembly files, where assembly code is written separately and linked with C++ code.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/c] And inline assembly, where assembly code is embedded within C++ code using compiler-specific extensions.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] In computer science, a **hash table** is a data structure that implements an associative array, also called a **dictionary** or simply **map**; an associative array is an abstract data type that maps keys to values.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] A hash table uses a hash function to compute an *index*, also called a *hash code*, into an array of *buckets* or *slots*, from which the desired value can be found.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] During lookup, the key is hashed and the resulting hash indicates where the corresponding value is stored.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] A map implemented by a hash table is called a **hash map**.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Most hash table designs employ an imperfect hash function.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Hash collisions, where the hash function generates the same index for more than one key, therefore typically must be accommodated in some way.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Common strategies to handle hash collisions include chaining, which stores multiple elements in the same slot using linked lists, and open addressing, which searches for the next available slot according to a probing sequence.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] In a well-dimensioned hash table, the average time complexity for each lookup is independent of the number of elements stored in the table.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Many hash table designs also allow arbitrary insertions and deletions of key–value pairs, at amortized constant average cost per operation.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Hashing is an example of a space–time tradeoff.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] If memory is infinite, the entire key can be used directly as an index to locate its value with a single memory access.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] On the other hand, if infinite time is available, values can be stored without regard for their keys, and a binary search or linear search can be used to retrieve the element.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] In many situations, hash tables turn out to be on average more efficient than search trees or any other table lookup structure.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] For this reason, they are widely used in many kinds of computer software, particularly for associative arrays, database indexing, caches, and sets.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Many programming languages provide built-in hash table structures, such as Python’s dictionaries, Java’s HashMap, C++’s unordered_map, Go maps, which abstract the complexity of hashing from the programmer.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The idea of hashing arose independently in different places.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] In January 1953, Hans Peter Luhn wrote an internal IBM memorandum that used hashing with chaining.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The first example of open addressing was proposed by A.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Around the same time, Gene Amdahl, Elaine M.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] McGraw, Nathaniel Rochester, and Arthur Samuel of IBM Research implemented hashing for the IBM 701 assembler.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Open addressing with linear probing is credited to Amdahl, although Andrey Ershov independently had the same idea.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The term "open addressing" was coined by W.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Wesley Peterson in his article which discusses the problem of search in large files.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The first published work on hashing with chaining is credited to Arnold Dumey, who discussed the idea of using remainder modulo a prime as a hash function.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The word "hashing" was first published in an article by Robert Morris.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] A theoretical analysis of linear probing was submitted originally by Konheim and Weiss.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] An associative array stores a set of (key, value) pairs and allows insertion, deletion, and lookup (search), with the constraint of unique keys.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] In the hash table implementation of associative arrays, an array A of length m is partially filled with n elements, where $m\geq n$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] A key **x** is hashed using a hash function h to compute an index location $A[h(x)]$ in the hash table, where $h(x)<m$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The efficiency of a hash table depends on the load factor, defined as the ratio of the number of stored elements to the number of available slots, with lower load factors generally yielding faster operations.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] At this index, both the key and its associated value are stored.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Storing the key alongside the value ensures that lookups can verify the key at the index to retrieve the correct value, even in the presence of collisions.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Under reasonable assumptions, hash tables have better time complexity bounds on search, delete, and insert operations in comparison to self-balancing binary search trees.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Hash tables are also commonly used to implement sets, by omitting the stored value for each key and merely tracking whether the key is present.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The performance of the hash table deteriorates in relation to the load factor $\alpha$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] In the limit of large m and n , each bucket statistically has a Poisson distribution with expectation $\lambda =\alpha$ for an ideally random hash function.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The software typically ensures that the load factor $\alpha$ remains below a certain constant, $\alpha _{\max }$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Therefore, a common approach is to resize or "rehash" the hash table whenever the load factor $\alpha$ reaches $\alpha _{\max }$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Similarly the table may also be resized if the load factor drops below $\alpha _{\max }/4$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] With separate chaining hash tables, each slot of the bucket array stores a pointer to a list or array of data.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Separate chaining hash tables suffer gradually declining performance as the load factor grows, and no fixed point beyond which resizing is absolutely needed.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] With separate chaining, the value of $\alpha _{\max }$ that gives best performance is typically between 1 and 3.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] With open addressing, each slot of the bucket array holds exactly one item.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Therefore an open-addressed hash table cannot have a load factor greater than 1.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The performance of open addressing becomes very bad when the load factor approaches 1.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Therefore a hash table that uses open addressing *must* be resized or *rehashed* if the load factor $\alpha$ approaches 1.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] With open addressing, acceptable figures of max load factor $\alpha _{\max }$ should range around 0.6 to 0.75.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] A hash function $h:U\rightarrow \{0,...,m-1\}$ maps the universe U of keys to indices or slots within the table, that is, $h(x)\in \{0,...,m-1\}$ for $x\in U$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The conventional implementations of hash functions are based on the *integer universe assumption* that all elements of the table stem from the universe $U=\{0,...,u-1\}$ , where the bit length of u is confined within the word size of a computer architecture.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] A hash function h is said to be perfect for a given set S if it is injective on S , that is, if each element $x\in S$ maps to a different value in ${0,...,m-1}$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] A perfect hash function can be created if all the keys are known ahead of time.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The schemes of hashing used in *integer universe assumption* include hashing by division, hashing by multiplication, universal hashing, dynamic perfect hashing, and static perfect hashing.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] However, hashing by division is the commonly used scheme.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The scheme in hashing by division is as follows: $h(x)\ =\ x\,{\bmod {\,}}m,$ where $h(x)$ is the hash value of $x\in S$ and m is the size of the table.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The scheme in hashing by multiplication is as follows: $h(x)=\lfloor m{\bigl (}(xA){\bmod {1}}{\bigr )}\rfloor$ Where A is a non-integer real-valued constant and m is the size of the table.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] An advantage of the hashing by multiplication is that the m is not critical.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Although any value A produces a hash function, Donald Knuth suggests using the golden ratio.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Commonly a string is used as a key to the hash function.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The third edition of *The C++ Programming Language* describes a simple hash function in which an unsigned integer that is initially zero is repeatedly left shifted one bit and then xor'ed with the integer value of the next character.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] This hash value is then taken modulo the table size.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] If the left shift is not circular, then the string length should be at least eight bits less than the size of the unsigned integer in bits.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Another common way to hash a string to an integer is with a polynomial rolling hash function.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Uniform distribution of the hash values is a fundamental requirement of a hash function.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] A non-uniform distribution increases the number of collisions and the cost of resolving them.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Uniformity is sometimes difficult to ensure by design, but may be evaluated empirically using statistical tests, e.g., a Pearson's chi-squared test for discrete uniform distributions.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The distribution needs to be uniform only for table sizes that occur in the application.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] In particular, if one uses dynamic resizing with exact doubling and halving of the table size, then the hash function needs to be uniform only when the size is a power of two.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Here the index can be computed as some range of bits of the hash function.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] On the other hand, some hashing algorithms prefer to have the size be a prime number.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] For open addressing schemes, the hash function should also avoid *runs*, the mapping of two or more keys to consecutive slots.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Such runs may cause the lookup cost to skyrocket, even if the load factor is low and collisions are infrequent.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The popular multiplicative hash is claimed to have particularly poor run behavior.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] K-independent hashing offers a way to prove a certain hash function does not have bad keysets for a given type of hashtable.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] A number of K-independence results are known for collision resolution schemes such as linear probing and cuckoo hashing.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Since K-independence can prove a hash function works, one can then focus on finding the fastest possible such hash function.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] A search algorithm that uses hashing consists of two parts.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The first part is computing a hash function which transforms the search key into an array index.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The ideal case is such that no two search keys hash to the same array index.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] However, this is not always the case and impossible to guarantee for unseen given data.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Hence the second part of the algorithm is collision resolution.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The two common methods for collision resolution are separate chaining and open addressing.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] In separate chaining, the process involves building a linked list with key–value pair for each search array index.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The collided items are chained together through a single linked list, which can be traversed to access the item with a unique search key.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Collision resolution through chaining with linked list is a common method of implementation of hash tables.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] If the element is comparable either numerically or lexically, and inserted into the list by maintaining the total order, it results in faster termination of the unsuccessful searches.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] If the keys are ordered, it could be efficient to use "self-organizing" concepts such as using a self-balancing binary search tree, through which the theoretical worst case could be brought down to $O(\log {n})$ , although it introduces additional complexities.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] In dynamic perfect hashing, two-level hash tables are used to reduce the look-up complexity to be a guaranteed $O(1)$ in the worst case.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] In this technique, the buckets of k entries are organized as perfect hash tables with $k^{2}$ slots providing constant worst-case lookup time, and low amortized time for insertion.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] A study shows array-based separate chaining to be 97% more performant when compared to the standard linked list method under heavy load.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Techniques such as using fusion tree for each buckets also result in constant time for all operations with high probability.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The linked list of separate chaining implementation may not be cache-conscious due to spatial locality—locality of reference—when the nodes of the linked list are scattered across memory, thus the list traversal during insert and search may entail CPU cache inefficiencies.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Open addressing is another collision resolution technique in which every entry record is stored in the bucket array itself, and the hash resolution is performed through **probing**.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] When a new entry has to be inserted, the buckets are examined, starting with the hashed-to slot and proceeding in some *probe sequence*, until an unoccupied slot is found.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] When searching for an entry, the buckets are scanned in the same sequence, until either the target record is found, or an unused array slot is found, which indicates an unsuccessful search.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The performance of open addressing may be slower compared to separate chaining since the probe sequence increases when the load factor $\alpha$ approaches 1.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The probing results in an infinite loop if the load factor reaches 1, in the case of a completely filled table.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The average cost of linear probing depends on the hash function's ability to distribute the elements uniformly throughout the table to avoid runs, since formation of runs would result in increased search time.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Since the slots are located in successive locations, linear probing could lead to better utilization of CPU cache due to locality of references resulting in reduced memory latency.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Coalesced hashing is a hybrid of both separate chaining and open addressing in which the buckets or nodes link within the table.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The algorithm is ideally suited for fixed memory allocation.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The collision in coalesced hashing is resolved by identifying the largest-indexed empty slot on the hash table, then the colliding value is inserted into that slot.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The bucket is also linked to the inserted node's slot which contains its colliding hash address.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Cuckoo hashing is a form of open addressing collision resolution technique which guarantees $O(1)$ worst-case lookup complexity and constant amortized time for insertions.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The collision is resolved through maintaining two hash tables, each having its own hashing function, and collided slot gets replaced with the given item, and the preoccupied element of the slot gets displaced into the other hash table.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The process continues until every key has its own spot in the empty buckets of the tables; if the procedure enters into infinite loop—which is identified through maintaining a threshold loop counter—both hash tables get rehashed with newer hash functions and the procedure continues.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Hopscotch hashing is an open addressing based algorithm which combines the elements of cuckoo hashing, linear probing and chaining through the notion of a *neighbourhood* of buckets—the subsequent buckets around any given occupied bucket, also called a "virtual" bucket.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The algorithm is designed to deliver better performance when the load factor of the hash table grows beyond 90%; it also provides high throughput in concurrent settings, thus well suited for implementing resizable concurrent hash table.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Each bucket within the hash table includes an additional "hop-information"—an *H*-bit bit array for indicating the relative distance of the item which was originally hashed into the current virtual bucket within *H* − 1 entries.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] *H* − 1, subsequent swap and hop-info bit array manipulation of each bucket is performed in accordance with its neighbourhood invariant properties.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Robin Hood hashing is an open addressing based collision resolution algorithm; the collisions are resolved through favouring the displacement of the element that is farthest—or longest *probe sequence length* (PSL)—from its "home location" i.e. the bucket to which the item was hashed into.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] It is named after Robin Hood, a mythical heroic outlaw who stole from the rich to give to the poor.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Although Robin Hood hashing does not change the theoretical search cost, it significantly affects the variance of the distribution of the items on the buckets, i.e. dealing with long run formation in the hash table.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Each node within the hash table that uses Robin Hood hashing should be augmented to store an extra PSL value.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] If a hash table becomes "too empty" after deleting some elements, resizing may be performed to avoid excessive memory usage.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Generally, a new hash table with a size double that of the original hash table gets allocated privately and every item in the original hash table gets moved to the newly allocated one by computing the hash values of the items followed by the insertion operation.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Rehashing is simple, but computationally expensive.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Some hash table implementations, notably in real-time systems, cannot pay the price of enlarging the hash table all at once, because it may interrupt time-critical operations.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] If one cannot avoid dynamic resizing, a solution is to perform the resizing gradually to avoid storage blip—typically at 50% of new table's size—during rehashing and to avoid memory fragmentation that triggers heap compaction due to deallocation of large memory blocks caused by the old hash table.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] In such case, the rehashing operation is done incrementally through extending prior memory block allocated for the old hash table such that the buckets of the hash table remain unaltered.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] A common approach for amortized rehashing involves maintaining two hash functions $h_{\text{old}}$ and $h_{\text{new}}$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Linear hashing is an implementation of the hash table which enables dynamic growths or shrinks of the table one bucket at a time.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The performance of a hash table is dependent on the hash function's ability in generating quasi-random numbers ( $\sigma$ ) for entries in the hash table where K , n and $h(x)$ denotes the key, number of buckets and the hash function such that $\sigma \ =\ h(K)\ \%\ n$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] If the hash function generates the same $\sigma$ for distinct keys ( $K_{1}\neq K_{2},\ h(K_{1})\ =\ h(K_{2})$ ), this results in *collision*, which is dealt with in a variety of ways.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The constant time complexity ( $O(1)$ ) of the operation in a hash table is presupposed on the condition that the hash function doesn't generate colliding indices; thus, the performance of the hash table is directly proportional to the chosen hash function's ability to disperse the indices.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] However, construction of such a hash function is practically infeasible, that being so, implementations depend on case-specific collision resolution techniques in achieving higher performance.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] The best performance is obtained in the case that the hash function distributes the elements of the universe uniformaly, and the elements stored at the table are drawn at random from the universe.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] In this case, in hashing with chaining, the expected time for a successful search is ${\textstyle 1+{\frac {\alpha }{2}}+\Theta \left({\frac {1}{m}}\right)}$ , and the expected time for an unsuccessful search is ${\textstyle e^{-\alpha }+\alpha +\Theta \left({\frac {1}{m}}\right)}$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Hash tables are commonly used to implement many types of in-memory tables.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] They are used to implement associative arrays.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Hash tables may also be used as disk-based data structures and database indices (such as in dbm) although B-trees are more popular in these applications.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Hash tables can be used to implement caches, auxiliary data tables that are used to speed up the access to data that is primarily stored in slower media.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] In this application, hash collisions can be handled by discarding one of the two colliding entries—usually erasing the old item that is currently stored in the table and overwriting it with the new item, so every item in the table has a unique hash value.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Hash tables can be used in the implementation of set data structure, which can store unique values without any particular order; set is typically used in testing the membership of a value in the collection, rather than element retrieval.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] A transposition table to a complex Hash Table which stores information about each section that has been searched.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/hash-table] Many programming languages provide hash table functionality, either as built-in associative arrays or as standard library modules.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] In computer programming, a **standard library** is the library made available across implementations of a programming language.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] Often, a standard library is specified by its associated programming language specification, however, some are set in part or whole by more informal practices of a language community.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] Some languages define a core part of the standard library that must be made available in all implementations while allowing other parts to be implemented optionally.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] In many languages, the standard library often has its own namespace.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] For example, C++, D, and Rust use `std::*` as the standard library namespace.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] However, in some like Python and Go, there is no "standard library namespace" or common prefix for modules belonging to the standard library.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] As defined with the core language aspects, the line between the core language and its standard library is relatively subtle.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] A programmer may confuse the two aspects even though the language designers intentionally separate the two.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] The line between the core language and its standard library is further blurred in some languages by defining core language constructs in terms of its standard library.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] For example, Java defines a string literal as an instance of the `java.lang.String` class.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] Smalltalk defines an anonymous function expression (a "block") as an instance of its library's `BlockContext` class.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] Scheme does not specify which portions must be implemented as core language vs. standard library.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] Philosophies of standard library design vary widely.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] This suggests a relatively small standard library, containing only the constructs that "every programmer" might reasonably require when building a large collection of software.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] This is the philosophy that is used in the C and C++ standard libraries.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] As a result, the C standard library and C++ Standard Library are significantly smaller in size and scope compared to, for instance, the Java standard library and C# standard library, which feature more extensive abilities.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] By contrast, Guido van Rossum, designer of Python, has embraced a much more inclusive vision of the standard library.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] Python attempts to offer an easy-to-code, object-oriented, high-level language.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] Van Rossum goes on to list libraries for processing XML, XML-RPC, email messages, and localization, facilities that the C++ Standard Library omits.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] This other philosophy is often found in scripting languages (as in Python or Ruby) or languages that use a virtual machine, such as Java or the .NET Framework languages.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] In C++, such facilities are not part of the standard library, but instead are included in other libraries, such as Boost or POCO.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/standard-library] In Java, the formerly standard libraries Java Platform, Enterprise Edition (now Jakarta EE) and JavaFX were moved to separate independent libraries.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] In computer programming, a **string** is traditionally a sequence of characters, either as a literal constant or as some kind of variable.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The latter may allow its elements to be mutated and the length changed, or it may be fixed (after creation).
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] A string is often implemented as an array data structure of bytes (or words) that stores a sequence of elements, typically characters, using some character encoding.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] More general, *string* may also denote a sequence (or list) of data other than just characters.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Depending on the programming language and precise data type used, a variable declared to be a string may either cause storage in memory to be statically allocated for a predetermined maximum length or employ dynamic allocation to allow it to hold a variable number of elements.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] When a string appears literally in source code, it is known as a string literal or an anonymous string.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] In formal languages, which are used in mathematical logic and theoretical computer science, a string is a finite sequence of symbols that are chosen from a set called an alphabet.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] A primary purpose of strings is to store human-readable text, like words and sentences.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Strings are used to communicate information from a computer program to the user of the program.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] A program may also accept string input from its user.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Further, strings may store data expressed as characters yet not intended for human reading.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The term string may also designate a sequence of data or computer records other than characters — like a "string of bits" — but when used without qualification it refers to strings of characters.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Use of the word "string" to mean any items arranged in a line, series or succession dates back centuries.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] In 19th-century typesetting, compositors used the term "string" to denote a length of type printed on paper; the string would be measured to determine the compositor's pay.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Use of the word "string" to mean "a sequence of symbols or linguistic elements in a definite order" emerged from mathematics, symbolic logic, and linguistic theory to speak about the formal behavior of symbolic systems, setting aside the symbols' meaning.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Sammet, "the first realistic string handling and pattern matching language" for computers was COMIT in the 1950s, followed by the SNOBOL language of the early 1960s.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] A **string datatype** is a datatype modeled on the idea of a formal string.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Strings are such an important and useful datatype that they are implemented in nearly every programming language.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] In some languages they are available as primitive types and in others as composite types.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The syntax of most high-level programming languages allows for a string, usually quoted in some way, to represent an instance of a string datatype; such a meta-string is called a *literal* or *string literal*.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Although formal strings can have an arbitrary finite length, the length of strings in real languages is often constrained to an artificial maximum.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Most strings in modern programming languages are variable-length strings.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Of course, even variable-length strings are limited in length by the amount of available memory.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The string length can be stored as a separate integer (which may put another artificial limit on the length) or implicitly through a termination character, usually a character value with all bits zero such as in C programming language.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] These character sets were typically based on ASCII or EBCDIC.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] If text in one encoding was displayed on a system using a different encoding, text was often mangled, though often somewhat readable and some computer users learned to read the mangled text.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Logographic languages such as Chinese, Japanese, and Korean (known collectively as CJK) need far more than 256 characters (the limit of a one 8-bit byte per-character encoding) for reasonable representation.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The normal solutions involved keeping single-byte representations for ASCII and using two-byte representations for CJK ideographs.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Use of these with existing code led to problems with matching and cutting of strings, the severity of which depended on how the character encoding was designed.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Some encodings such as the EUC family guarantee that a byte value in the ASCII range will represent only that ASCII character, making the encoding safe for systems that use those characters as field separators.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Other encodings such as ISO-2022 and Shift-JIS do not make such guarantees, making matching on byte codes unsafe.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] These encodings also were not "self-synchronizing", so that locating character boundaries required backing up to the start of a string, and pasting two strings together could result in corruption of the second string.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Unicode has simplified the picture somewhat.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Most programming languages now have a datatype for Unicode strings.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Unicode's preferred byte stream format UTF-8 is designed not to have the problems described above for older multibyte encodings.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Some languages, such as C++, Perl and Ruby, normally allow the contents of a string to be changed after it has been created; these are termed *mutable* strings.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] In other languages, such as Java, JavaScript, Lua, Python, and Go, the value is fixed and a new string must be created if any alteration is to be made; these are termed *immutable* strings.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Some of these languages with immutable strings also provide another type that is mutable, such as Java and .NET's `StringBuilder`, the thread-safe Java `StringBuffer`, and the Cocoa `NSMutableString`.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Immutability brings advantages and disadvantages: while immutable strings may require inefficiently creating many copies, they are simpler and fully thread-safe.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Strings are typically implemented as arrays of bytes, characters, or code units, to allow fast access to individual units or substrings, including characters when they have a fixed length.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] A few languages such as Haskell implement them as linked lists instead.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Many high-level languages provide strings as a primitive data type, such as JavaScript and PHP, while most others provide them as a composite data type, some with special language support in writing literals, for example, Java and C#.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Some languages, such as C, Prolog and Erlang, avoid implementing a dedicated string datatype at all, instead adopting the convention of representing strings as lists of character codes.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Even in programming languages having a dedicated string type, strings can usually be iterated as a sequence of character codes, like lists of integers or other values.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Representations of strings depend heavily on the choice of character repertoire and the method of character encoding.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Older string implementations were designed to work with repertoire and encoding defined by ASCII, or more recent extensions like the ISO 8859 series.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Modern implementations often use the extensive repertoire defined by Unicode along with a variety of complex encodings such as UTF-8 and UTF-16.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The term *byte string* usually indicates a general-purpose string of bytes, rather than strings of only (readable) characters, strings of bits, or such.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Byte strings often imply that bytes can take any value and any data can be stored as-is, meaning that there should be no value interpreted as a termination value.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Most string implementations are very similar to variable-length arrays with the entries storing the character codes of corresponding characters.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The principal difference is that, with certain encodings, a single logical character may take up more than one entry in the array.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] This happens, for example, with UTF-8, where single codes (UCS code points) can take anywhere from one to four bytes, and single characters can take an arbitrary number of codes.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] In these cases, the logical length of the string (number of characters) differs from the physical length of the array (number of bytes in use).
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] UTF-32 avoids the first part of the problem.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The length of a string can be stored in a dope vector, separate from the storage holding the actual characters.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The IBM PL/I (F) compiler used a **string dope vector** (SDV) for variable-length strings and for passing string parameters.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The SDV contains a current length and a maximum length, and is not adjacent to the string proper.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] After PL/I (F), IBM dropped the SDV in favor of length-prefixed strings.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The length of a string can be stored implicitly by using a special terminating character; often this is the null character (NUL), which has all bits zero, a convention used and perpetuated by the popular C programming language.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Hence, this representation is commonly referred to as a **C string**.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] This representation of an *n*-character string takes *n* + 1 space (1 for the terminator), and is thus an implicit data structure.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] In terminated strings, the terminating code is not an allowable character in any string.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Strings with *length* field do not have this limitation and can also store arbitrary binary data.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The length of the string in the above example, "`FRANK`", is 5 characters, but it occupies 6 bytes.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Characters after the terminator do not form part of the representation; they may be either part of other data or just garbage.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Using a special byte other than null for terminating strings has historically appeared in both hardware and software, though sometimes with a value that was also a printing character.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] `$` was used by many assembler systems, `:` used by CDC systems (this character had a value of zero), and the ZX80 used `"` since this was the string delimiter in its BASIC language.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Somewhat similar, "data processing" machines like the IBM 1401 used a special word mark bit to delimit strings at the left, where the operation would start at the right.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] This bit had to be clear in all other parts of the string.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] This meant that, while the IBM 1401 had a seven-bit word, almost no-one ever thought to use this as a feature, and override the assignment of the seventh bit to (for example) handle ASCII codes.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Early microcomputer software relied upon the fact that ASCII codes do not use the high-order bit, and set it to indicate the end of a string.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The length of a string can also be stored explicitly, for example by prefixing the string with the length as a byte value.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] This convention is used in many Pascal dialects; as a consequence, some people call such a string a **Pascal string** or **P-string**.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Storing the string length as byte limits the maximum string length to 255.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] To avoid such limitations, improved implementations of P-strings use 16-, 32-, or 64-bit words to store the string length.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] When the *length* field covers the address space, strings are limited only by the available memory.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] If the length is not bounded, encoding a length *n* takes log(*n*) space (see fixed-length code), so length-prefixed strings are a succinct data structure, encoding a string of length *n* in log(*n*) + *n* space.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] In the latter case, the length-prefix field itself does not have fixed length, therefore the actual string data needs to be moved when the string grows such that the length field needs to be increased.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] However, since the implementation is usually hidden, the string must be accessed and modified through member functions.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] `text` is a pointer to a dynamically allocated memory area, which might be expanded as needed.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Both character termination and length codes limit strings: For example, C character arrays that contain null (NUL) characters cannot be handled directly by C string library functions: Strings using a length code are limited to the maximum value of the length code.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Both of these limitations can be overcome by clever programming.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] It is possible to create data structures and functions that manipulate them that do not have the problems associated with character termination and can in principle overcome length code bounds.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] It is also possible to optimize the string represented using techniques from run length encoding (replacing repeated characters by the character value and a length) and Hamming encoding.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] While these representations are common, others are possible.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Using ropes makes certain string operations, such as insertions, deletions, and concatenations more efficient.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The core data structure in a text editor is the one that manages the string (sequence of characters) that represents the current state of the file being edited.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The differing memory layout and storage requirements of strings can affect the security of the program accessing the string data.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] String representations requiring a terminating character are commonly susceptible to buffer overflow problems if the terminating character is not present, caused by a coding error or an attacker deliberately altering the data.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] String representations adopting a separate length field are also susceptible if the length can be manipulated.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] In such cases, program code accessing the string data requires bounds checking to ensure that it does not inadvertently access or change data outside of the string memory limits.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] String data is frequently obtained from user input to a program.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] As such, it is the responsibility of the program to validate the string to ensure that it represents the expected format.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Performing limited or no validation of user input can cause a program to be vulnerable to code injection attacks.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Sometimes, strings need to be embedded inside a text file that is both human-readable and intended for consumption by a machine.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] This is needed in, for example, source code of programming languages, or in configuration files.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] In this case, the NUL character does not work well as a terminator since it is normally invisible (non-printable) and is difficult to input via a keyboard.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Storing the string length would also be inconvenient as manual computation and tracking of the length is tedious and error-prone.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] While character strings are very common uses of strings, a string in computer science may refer generically to any sequence of homogeneously typed data.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] A bit string or byte string, for example, may be used to represent non-textual binary data retrieved from a communications medium.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] This data may or may not be represented by a string-specific datatype, depending on the needs of the application, the desire of the programmer, and the capabilities of the programming language being used.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] If the programming language's string implementation is not 8-bit clean, data corruption may ensue.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] C programmers draw a sharp distinction between a "string", aka a "string of characters", which by definition is always null terminated, vs. an "array of characters" which may be stored in the same array but is often not null terminated.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Using C string handling functions on such an array of characters often seems to work, but later leads to security problems.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] There are many algorithms for processing strings, each with various trade-offs.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Competing algorithms can be analyzed with respect to run time, storage requirements, and so forth.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The name **stringology** was coined in 1984 by computer scientist Zvi Galil for the theory of algorithms and data structures used for string processing.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Advanced string algorithms often employ complex mechanisms and data structures, among them suffix trees and finite-state machines.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Character strings are such a useful datatype that several languages have been designed in order to make string processing applications easy to write.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Many Unix utilities perform simple string manipulations and can be used to easily program some powerful string processing algorithms.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Files and finite streams may be viewed as strings.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Some APIs like Multimedia Control Interface, embedded SQL or printf use strings to hold commands that will be interpreted.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Many scripting programming languages, including Perl, Python, Ruby, and Tcl employ regular expressions to facilitate text operations.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Perl is particularly noted for its regular expression use, and many other languages and applications implement Perl compatible regular expressions.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Some languages such as Perl and Ruby support string interpolation, which permits arbitrary expressions to be evaluated and included in string literals.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] String functions are used to create strings or change the contents of a mutable string.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] They also are used to query information about a string.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The set of functions and their names varies depending on the computer programming language.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The most basic example of a string function is the string length function – the function that returns the length of a string (not counting any terminator characters or any of the string's internal structural information) and does not modify the string.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] This function is often named `length`, `len`, or `size`.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] For example, `length("hello world")` would return 11.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Another common function is concatenation, where a new string is created by appending two strings, often this is the + addition operator.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Some microprocessor's instruction set architectures contain direct support for string operations, such as block copy (e.g.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Let $\Sigma$ be a finite set of distinct, unambiguous symbols (alternatively called characters), called the alphabet.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] A **string** (or **word** or **expression**) over $\Sigma$ is any finite sequence of symbols from $\Sigma$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The *length* of a string s is the number of symbols in s (the length of the sequence) and can be any non-negative integer; it is often denoted as $|s|$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The *empty string* is the unique string over $\Sigma$ of length 0 , and is denoted $\varepsilon$ or $\lambda$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The set of all strings over $\Sigma$ of length n is denoted $\Sigma ^{n}$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] We have $\Sigma ^{0}=\{\varepsilon \}$ for every alphabet $\Sigma$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The set of all strings over $\Sigma$ of any length is the Kleene closure of $\Sigma$ and is denoted $\Sigma ^{*}$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Although the set $\Sigma ^{*}$ itself is countably infinite, each element of $\Sigma ^{*}$ is a string of finite length.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] A set of strings over $\Sigma$ (i.e. any subset of $\Sigma ^{*}$ ) is called a *formal language* over $\Sigma$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] String concatenation is an associative, but non-commutative operation.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The empty string $\varepsilon$ serves as the identity element; for any string s , $\varepsilon s=s\varepsilon =s$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Therefore, the set $\Sigma ^{*}$ and the concatenation operation form a monoid, the free monoid generated by $\Sigma$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] In addition, the length function defines a monoid homomorphism from $\Sigma ^{*}$ to the non-negative integers (that is, a function $L:\Sigma ^{*}\mapsto \mathbb {N} \cup \{0\}$ , such that $L(st)=L(s)+L(t)\quad \forall s,t\in \Sigma ^{*}$ ).
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] A string s is said to be a *substring* or *factor* of t if there exist (possibly empty) strings u and v such that $t=usv$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The relation "is a substring of" defines a partial order on $\Sigma ^{*}$ , the least element of which is the empty string.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] A string s is said to be a prefix of t if there exists a string u such that $t=su$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] If u is nonempty, s is said to be a *proper* prefix of t .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Symmetrically, a string s is said to be a suffix of t if there exists a string u such that $t=us$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] If u is nonempty, s is said to be a *proper* suffix of t .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Suffixes and prefixes are substrings of t .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Both the relations "is a prefix of" and "is a suffix of" are prefix orders.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The reverse of a string is a string with the same symbols but in reverse order.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] For example, if $s={\texttt {abc}}$ (where ${\texttt {a}}$ , ${\texttt {b}}$ , and ${\texttt {c}}$ are symbols of the alphabet), then the reverse of s is ${\texttt {cba}}$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] A string that is the reverse of itself (e.g., $s={\texttt {madam}}$ ) is called a palindrome, which also includes the empty string and all strings of length 1 .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] A string $s=uv$ is said to be a rotation of t if $t=vu$ .
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] It is often useful to define an ordering on a set of strings.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] If the alphabet $\Sigma$ has a total order (cf. alphabetical order) one can define a total order on $\Sigma ^{*}$ called lexicographical order.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The lexicographical order is total if the alphabetical order is, but is not well-founded for any nontrivial alphabet, even if the alphabetical order is.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] See Shortlex for an alternative string ordering that preserves well-foundedness.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] A number of additional operations on strings commonly occur in the formal theory.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] These are given in the article on string operations.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] The natural topology on the set of fixed-length strings or variable-length strings is the discrete topology, but the natural topology on the set of infinite strings is the limit topology, viewing the set of infinite strings as the inverse limit of the sets of finite strings.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] This is the construction used for the *p*-adic numbers and some constructions of the Cantor set, and yields the same topology.
[src:abseil-cpp-lib/string-computer-science] Isomorphisms between string representations of topologies can be found by normalizing according to the lexicographically minimal string rotation.
